T1  - Financial Development and Intersectoral Allocation: A New Approach
AU  - FISMAN, RAYMOND
AU  - LOVE, INESSA
Y1  - 2004/12/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2004.00716.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2785
EP  - 2807
VL  - 59
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2004.00716.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT This paper uses a new methodology based on industry comovement to examine the role of financial market development in intersectoral allocation. Based on the assumption that there exist common global shocks to growth opportunities, we hypothesize that country pairs should have correlated patterns of sectoral growth if they are able to respond to these shocks. Consistent with financial markets promoting responsiveness to shocks, countries have more highly correlated growth rates across sectors when both countries have well-developed financial markets. This effect is stronger between country pairs at similar levels of economic development, which are more likely to experience similar growth shocks.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Systemic Risk and International Portfolio Choice
AU  - DAS, SANJIV RANJAN
AU  - UPPAL, RAMAN
Y1  - 2004/12/01
PY  - 2004
DA  - 2004/12/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2004.00717.x
T2  - The Journal of Finance
JF  - The Journal of Finance
JO  - The Journal of Finance
SP  - 2809
EP  - 2834
VL  - 59
IS  - 6
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0022-1082
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1540-6261.2004.00717.x
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - ABSTRACT Returns on international equities are characterized by jumps; moreover, these jumps tend to occur at the same time across countries leading to systemic risk. We capture these stylized facts using a multivariate system of jump-diffusion processes where the arrival of jumps is simultaneous across assets. We then determine an investor's optimal portfolio for this model of returns. Systemic risk has two effects: One, it reduces the gains from diversification and two, it penalizes investors for holding levered positions. We find that the loss resulting from diminished diversification is small, while that from holding very highly levered positions is large.
ER  - 

